The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brownish and water-flagging mice at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special callers will be located at major locations around the property to track bat activity through the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
The sound analyses of all recordings by experts will determine the frequency of the bat calls and the species doing what.
A habitat map and a report will then be drawn up to provide a detailed landscape picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will be included in the decision on the measures to be taken, such as the installation of pastures and the best management of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has sunk considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and works affecting breeding sites and habitat reduction.
Windmills and lighting may also present a risk, same as fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials and attacks from hake tax.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes for catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and roadside obstacles when they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten qualified experts who regularly carry out surveys, screening of breeding sites and, among other things, rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at the Three Landersendom in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threeave we have a perfect area for bats," he says.
‘We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes the importance of mapping the bats before carrying out maintenance on a property since the accidental destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young people, and perhaps exterminate an entire local population.
Flag mice are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or disturb them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish employee of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the audience to help in the work.
She says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we just don't know how the populations are doing."
