Algae flowering update: the concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Commission for Fisheries and Animal Life (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County — indicating reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae stretches about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots are discovered about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Rødalger has also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations on or off the coast of Pinellas County have been reported during the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations on or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier County.
No respiratory irritation was reported in the northwest of Florida in the last week.
